Shared Qs (u12)


  1. Question

    A circle with radius \(r=9\) centimeters is cut into 3 congruent sectors. A length of red string is pulled around the circle, and the string is exactly long enough to span the arc of 2 adjacent sectors, as shown in the diagram below.


    How long, in centimeters, is the red string? Please answer as a decimal approximation accurate within \(\pm 0.01\) centimeters.


    Solution

    Find the diameter.

    \[d=2r\] \[d=2\cdot9\] \[d=18\]

    Find the circumference.

    \[C = \pi d\] \[C = \pi \cdot 18\] \[C~\approx~56.5486678\]

    The string’s length is \(\frac{2}{3}\) of the circumference.

    \[L~=~\frac{2}{3}C\] \[L~=~\frac{2}{3}d\pi\] \[L~=~\frac{2}{3}2\pi r\] \[L~\approx~\frac{2}{3}(56.5486678)\] \[L~\approx~37.6991118\]

  11. Question

    A length of red string is pulled around the circle with radius \(r=6\). The red string subtends a central angle with a degree measure of \(\psi\)°, and the red string also subtends an inscribed angle with degree measure of 98°.


    How long, in centimeters, is the red string? Please answer as a decimal approximation accurate within \(\pm 0.01\) centimeters.


    Solution

    The inscribed angle theorem states that an angle \(\theta\) inscribed in a circle is half of the central angle \(2\theta\) that intercepts the same arc on the circle. Surprisingly, this is independent of where the inscribed angle sits on the circle. I find this animation helpful. Please take a moment to internalize this theorem, as it shows up frequently on standardized tests.

    Anyway, for this problem, from the inscribed-angle theorem, we know \(\psi=2\cdot 98=196\). In other words, our central angle is twice the corresponding inscribed angle.

    Find the diameter.

    \[d=2r\] \[d=2\cdot6\] \[d=12\]

    Find the circumference.

    \[C = \pi d\] \[C = \pi \cdot 12\] \[C~\approx~37.6991118\]

    Remember, there are \(360^{\circ}\) in a full circle. The string’s length is \(\frac{196}{360}\) of the circumference.

    \[L~=~\frac{196}{360}C\] \[L~=~\frac{196}{360}d\pi\] \[L~=~\frac{196}{360}2\pi r\] \[L~\approx~\frac{196}{360}(37.6991118)\] \[L~\approx~20.525072\]

  16. Question

    Two concentric circles have radii \(r_1=1\) meters and \(r_2=3.79\) meters. A central angle subtends similar arcs on both circles: a blue arc on the smaller circle and a red arc on the larger circle. The blue arc length is 1.12 meters, as shown in the diagram below.


    What is the length, in meters, of the red arc? The tolerance is set to \(\pm0.01\) meters.


    Solution

    Okay, this might seem absurdly easy if you are comfortable with similarity.

    \[\frac{1}{1.12} ~=~ \frac{3.79}{?}\]

    \[?~=~ 1.12\cdot 3.79 ~=~ 4.2448\]

    I am trying to introduce the radian, which is the arc length of a unit circle.

    • Massachusetts learning objective F-TF.A.1:
      • Understand radian measure of an angle as the length of the arc on the unit circle subtended by the angle.

    In this case, the central angle is 64°, which is approximately equivalent to 1.12 radians. To convert between degrees and radians, we can multiply by \(\frac{\pi}{180^{\circ}}\) to go from degrees to radians or multiply by \(\frac{180^{\circ}}{\pi}\) to convert from radians to degrees.

    As you progress in math, you’ll use radians by default, not degrees. One of the best reasons for this depends on concepts learned in calculus… but in short… if we use radians, then the derivative of \(\sin(x)\) is simply \(\cos(x)\). If we used degrees, then calculus with trigonometric functions would be more annoying.

    If you look up circular arc on wikipedia, you’ll see a formula relating the arc length (\(L\)) to radius (\(r\)) and the central angle measured in radians (\(\theta\)). \[L~=~r\theta\]

    So, in our case:

    \[L~=~(3.79)(1.12)\]

    \[L~=~4.2448~\text{m}\]

  21. Question

    Okay, this might seem absurdly easy if you are comfortable with similarity.

    \[\frac{1}{?} ~=~ \frac{3.11}{8.83}\]

    \[?~=~ \frac{8.83}{3.11} ~=~ 2.8392283\]

    I am trying to introduce the radian, which is the arc length of a unit circle.

      • Understand radian measure of an angle as the length of the arc on the unit circle subtended by the angle.

    \[5.79~=~(3.99)(\theta)\]

    \[\theta~=~\frac{5.79}{3.99}~=~ 1.4511278\]

  31. Question

    Consider a circle with a radius of length \(r=7.2\) meters. A central angle, in standard position, subtends an arc of length \(14.4\) meters.


    Find \(\theta\) in radians.


    Solution

    Remember, the radian measure of an angle is the length of the arc on the unit circle subtended by the angle. The circle shown is not a unit circle (its radius is 7.2), but we can add a unit circle into the drawing.

    (Not drawn to scale.)


    \[\frac{\theta}{14.4}~=~\frac{1}{7.2}\]

    \[\theta~=~\frac{14.4}{7.2}~=~2\]

    If you refer to the wikipedia article on circular arcs, you’ll see a formula: \[L=\theta r\] where \(L\) is an arc length on a circle of radius \(r\) and with central angle \(\theta\) (pronounced “theta”). In our case, we were given \(L=14.4\) and \(r=7.2\), so we can rearrange the formula, solving for \(\theta\).

    \[\theta = \frac{L}{r} = \frac{14.4}{7.2}\]

    \[360^{\circ}~=~2\pi \text{ radians}~=~1\text{ turn}\]

    The angle is \(105^{\circ}\), which is \(\frac{7}{12}\pi\) radians, approximately 1.83259571459405 radians, which is \(\frac{7}{24}\) of a turn, which is 0.291666666666667 turns.



  40. Question

    For each diagram below, a circle is sliced into congruent sectors. An angle, which subtends an integer count of the sectors, is indicated by an circular arc near the center of the circle. You will determine the measure of the angle using degrees, radians, and (fractions of) turns. All radian measures will be expressed in exact form, as a fraction of \(\pi\). All fractions will be shown in reduced form, using improper fractions instead of mixed numbers.

    Unlike temperature, where Fahrenheit and Celsius disagree on 0, all three units of angle measure agree on 0. All three measures grow linearly with arc length of a unit circle, so conversions are simple proportions, and the conversion factors can be expressed with the following equivalences.

    \[360^{\circ}~=~2\pi \text{ radians}~=~1\text{ turn}\]

    Express the following angles using degrees, radians, and turns.

    Circle 1

    • The circle below is cut into 4 congruent sectors. The central angle, \(\theta\) (theta), subtends 3 of the sectors.

    • The angle is degrees.

    • The angle is \(\pi\bigg/\) radians.

    • As a decimal approximation, the angle is radians.

    • The angle is \(\bigg/\) turns.

    • As a decimal, the angle is turns.

    Circle 2

    • The circle below is cut into 24 congruent sectors. The central angle, \(\phi\) (phi), subtends 13 of the sectors.

    • The angle is degrees.

    • The angle is \(\pi\bigg/\) radians.

    • As a decimal approximation, the angle is radians.

    • The angle is \(\bigg/\) turns.

    • As a decimal, the angle is turns.

    Circle 3

    • The circle below is cut into 18 congruent sectors. The central angle, \(\omega\) (omega), subtends 5 of the sectors.

    • The angle is degrees.

    • The angle is \(\pi\bigg/\) radians.

    • As a decimal approximation, the angle is radians.

    • The angle is \(\bigg/\) turns.

    • As a decimal, the angle is turns.

    Circle 4

    • The circle below is cut into 20 congruent sectors. The central angle, \(\psi\) (psi), subtends 16 of the sectors.

    • The angle is degrees.

    • The angle is \(\pi\bigg/\) radians.

    • As a decimal approximation, the angle is radians.

    • The angle is \(\bigg/\) turns.

    Circle 5

    Solution

    Circle 1

    The angle is \(270^{\circ}\), which is \(\frac{3}{2}\pi\) radians, approximately 4.71238898038469 radians, which is \(\frac{3}{4}\) of a turn, which is 0.75 turns.

    Circle 2

    • The circle is cut into 24 congruent sectors. The central angle, \(\phi\) (phi), subtends 13 of the sectors.

    The angle is \(195^{\circ}\), which is \(\frac{13}{12}\pi\) radians, approximately 3.40339204138894 radians, which is \(\frac{13}{24}\) of a turn, which is 0.541666666666667 turns.

    Circle 3

    • The circle is cut into 18 congruent sectors. The central angle, \(\omega\) (omega), subtends 5 of the sectors.

    The angle is \(100^{\circ}\), which is \(\frac{5}{9}\pi\) radians, approximately 1.74532925199433 radians, which is \(\frac{5}{18}\) of a turn, which is 0.277777777777778 turns.

    Circle 4

    • The circle is cut into 20 congruent sectors. The central angle, \(\psi\) (psi), subtends 16 of the sectors.

    The angle is \(288^{\circ}\), which is \(\frac{8}{5}\pi\) radians, approximately 5.02654824574367 radians, which is \(\frac{4}{5}\) of a turn, which is 0.8 turns.

    Circle 5

    • The circle is cut into 8 congruent sectors. The central angle, \(\beta\) (beta), subtends 2 of the sectors.

    The angle is \(90^{\circ}\), which is \(\frac{1}{2}\pi\) radians, approximately 1.5707963267949 radians, which is \(\frac{1}{4}\) of a turn, which is 0.25 turns.
